  "text": "'2Figure 4 suggests that not only do prime-age people consume less housing relative to their income than do those younger and alder; but also older people consume more housing relative to their income than do younger people. Louis 8. [CITATION_1] points ant that older people have been major contributors to housing trends because of the rising rate of household (as opposed to individual) incidence in that age-group. The decision not to disband existing households when a spouse retires or dies means that older people continue to occupy the existing housing stock, which rewires ~ounw households to buv new rather than &i&ho&s and, thus, for thereio be more housing investment. 1954: l-1988:4 (1954: l-1988 : 3 for durable expenditures when leads are used). Numbers in parentheses are L statistics (in absolute value). For the housing-investment equation, R, YTR/POP, W, P, Q, and YD/POP are lagged one quarter. Statistics reported at the bottom of the table: X2: test of the hypothesis that the coefficients of Z,, and Z,, are zero; critical values (d.f. = 2) are 5.99 at the S-percent level and 9.21 at the l-percent level; j*: value of j for which wi is at a minimum; X2(lags): X\" value for the equation with the lagged values of all the explanatory variables added (including the lagged value of the lagged dependent variable and the lagged value of the lagged stock variable), except for ZI, and Z,,; X%eads): X\" value for the equation with the values of R, YTR/POP, W, P, Q, and YD/POP led one quarter added for durable expenditures and the contemporaneous values added for housing investment.",
